nge of issues, including the Golden Age of television drama, McCarthy-era blacklisting, the rise and fall of Edward R. Murrow, quiz show scandals, children's programming, and the impact of television on American life and of television criticism on the medium itself. Lewis Gould also supplies a brief biography of his father that assesses his influence on the evolution of television, as well as prefaces to each section.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aTelevision broadcastingzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aTelevision programszUnited StatesvReviews. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aGould, Lewis L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGould, Lewis L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/72844840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292784512423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292784512/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK